All right. So question for the group. What is the magnitude of being five minutes early versus

00:20:53.599 --> 00:20:59.280
five minutes late? Or what's the, what are the different impacts of being five minutes early

00:20:59.280 --> 00:21:12.239
versus five minutes late? Yeah, missing a reservation. Yeah. If I show up five minutes

00:21:12.239 --> 00:21:19.119
early, I'm going to make my table. If I show up five minutes late, maybe, maybe not. If I show

00:21:19.119 --> 00:21:23.439
up 20 minutes early, I'm definitely going to make my table, but I just wasted 20 minutes of my life.

00:21:23.920 --> 00:21:26.959
If I show up 20 minutes late, I'm definitely going to miss my table.

00:21:28.319 --> 00:21:32.400
And so even though you're wrong in the same way, you're 20 minutes off,

00:21:33.040 --> 00:21:38.880
the impact is very, very different. And that's one of the real powers of Monte Carlo simulation

00:21:38.880 --> 00:21:44.319
is you can see, hey, if I am wrong on my inputs, I'm going to be wrong on my outputs, but I'm going

00:21:44.319 --> 00:21:48.560
to be wrong in different ways. And that really helps drive the conversations around how does

00:21:48.560 --> 00:21:54.400
this impact our operations? Like, am I okay being 20 minutes early, but not 20 minutes late? Maybe I

